Let's get to it.
Today=E2=80=99s Not Boring is brought to you by=E2=80=A6 Speakeasy [ https:=
//substack.com/redirect/b53529a6-9bb0-4f7d-8d56-5b639672b533?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOX=
AwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
As the old saying goes, =E2=80=9CGet someone to use your product, get a use=
r for a day; get someone to integrate your API, get a customer for life.=E2=
=80=9D Or something like that.=C2=A0
I=E2=80=99ve been a fan of the API-first business model since writing about=
 it back in 2020 [ https://substack.com/redirect/51125476-f2b8-4d58-92eb-d4=
56ba478d43?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRN=
pU ]. Half the battle is building APIs that handle mission critical but non=
-core work for your customers. The other half is making it as easy for them=
 to integrate your APIs as possible. Speakeasy [ https://substack.com/redir=
ect/b53529a6-9bb0-4f7d-8d56-5b639672b533?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_=
ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] can help integrate API users 50% faster.=
=C2=A0
Creating a frictionless API experience for your partners and customers no l=
onger requires an army of engineers. Speakeasy=E2=80=99s platform makes cra=
fting type-safe, idiomatic client libraries for enterprise APIs easy. That =
means you can unlock API revenue while keeping your team focused on what ma=
tters most: shipping new products. Make SDK generation part of your API=E2=
=80=99s CI/CD and distribute libraries that users love at a fraction of the=
 cost of maintaining them in-house. Let Speakeasy handle your mission-criti=
cal, non-core work so you can do the same for your customers.=C2=A0
If you know what any of those terms meant, and if those pain points sound f=
amiliar, you should check out Speakeasy [ https://substack.com/redirect/b53=
529a6-9bb0-4f7d-8d56-5b639672b533?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZ=
jmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].
(1) TSMC=E2=80=99s Arizona Chip Production Yields Surpass Taiwan=E2=80=99s =
in Win for US Push [ https://substack.com/redirect/1c032876-2c9f-4583-a781-=
3b5200286a01?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8Exk=
RNpU ]
Mackenzie Hawkins for Bloomberg
Writing the Weekly Dose is hard. We have the whole thing written and ready =
to go, and then boom: Bloomberg reports that TSMC=E2=80=99s Arizona manufac=
turing facility is producing chips at 4% higher yields than similar facilit=
ies in Taiwan.=20
That is huge. We=E2=80=99re optimists, and frankly, we were a little worrie=
d about TSMC=E2=80=99s ability to manufacture here. Less skilled labor, saf=
ety and management issues, all the things that normally get in the way of b=
uilding things. TSMC pushed back its plans to start full production here by=
 a year, then pushed back the launch date for the second fab.=20
And then they go and totally redeem themselves. Now, these are 4nm chips, n=
ot the 3nm chips TSMC makes at home, but a 4% improvement in yields shows t=
hat we can manufacture these complex little wafers here, might unlock billi=
ons in additional CHIPS Act funding, and might push TSMC to open all six po=
ssible fabs in Phoenix.=20
The way things are heading, we=E2=80=99re going to produce oodles of chips =
powered by gigawatts of nuclear energy while eagles fly overhead, kids eat =
apple pie, and someone terraforms the Arizona dessert in the background. Ou=
t with the longshoremen, in with the onshoremen.=20
(2) Evaluation of the lithium resource in the Smackover Formation brines of=
 southern Arkansas using machine learning [ https://substack.com/redirect/2=
6db5844-3ca6-4f76-9309-2ce2b59f8344?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNua=
MZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Knierim et al in Science
We calculated that there are 5.1 to 19 million tons of lithium in Smackover=
 Formation brines in southern Arkansas.
About 6 weeks ago, we covered the lithium boom in the the Smackover Formati=
on region of the United States. That story covered how one particular entre=
preneur was planning to use Direct Lithium Extraction, a methodology he dev=
eloped back in the 90s, across one particular region of the southeast refer=
red to as the Smackover Foundation.
A paper recently published in Science confirmed that that entrepreneur is o=
n the right track. The researchers identified a substantial lithium resourc=
e in southern Arkansas. Using an AI model trained on geological, geochemica=
l, and temperature data, the team predicted lithium concentrations across t=
he region and estimated the formation contains between 5.1 and 19 million t=
ons of lithium, or about 35% to 136% of the current U.S. lithium resource e=
stimate. Lithium boom baby!
If the U.S. is going to usher in a clean, renewable future, it=E2=80=99s go=
ing to need access to a lot more lithium =E2=80=94 the essential mineral fo=
r building EV batteries and other clean tech. And boy does it look like Ark=
ansas has us covered. God blessed America.=20
(3) Carbon dioxide capture from open air using covalent organic frameworks =
[ https://substack.com/redirect/8b29f3b7-bb2c-44e9-a502-ea725b6504ce?j=3Dey=
J1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Zhou et al in Nature
Here a porous, crystalline covalent organic framework (COF) with olefin lin=
kages has been synthesized, structurally characterized and post-synthetical=
ly modified by the covalent attachment of amine initiators for producing po=
lyamines within the pores. This COF (termed COF-999) can capture CO2 from o=
pen air. COF-999 has a capacity of 0.96=E2=80=89mmol under dry conditions a=
nd 2.05=E2=80=89mmol=E2=80=89g=E2=80=931 under 50% relative humidity, both =
from 400=E2=80=89ppm CO2. This COF was tested for more than 100 adsorption=
=E2=80=93desorption cycles in the open air of Berkeley, California, and fou=
nd to fully retain its performance.
Having access to abundant lithium would likely reduce our CO2 emissions in =
the future. But we=E2=80=99ll still need technologies that capture and remo=
ve the CO2 that has and will continue to make its way out into the world.=
=20
Luckily, Cal Berkeley researchers have developed COF-999, a new porous, cry=
stalline organic material that efficiently captures carbon dioxide directly=
 from open air. The material functions like a specialized sponge made of a =
porous material, with tiny holes throughout. These pores are designed to se=
lectively attract and trap carbon dioxide molecules from the air as it pass=
es through. Then, when the material is gently heated, it releases the captu=
red CO=E2=82=82, allowing COF-999 to be reused for continuous carbon captur=
e.
Someone like Terraform Industries or Valar Atomics can turn the CO=E2=82=82=
 into fuel, that fuel will be used to power planes, and those planes can ke=
ep sprinkling COF-999. Bad time to be carbon dioxide. Good time to be a hum=
an.=20
(4) Science Announces Positive Preliminary Results For Vision Restoration I=
n Pivotal Clinical Trial [ https://substack.com/redirect/7850b0b0-61df-4cda=
-a416-745ceb181253?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-=
6m8ExkRNpU ]
Science Corporation, a leader in brain-computer interface (=E2=80=9CBCI=E2=
=80=9D) technology, has announced the preliminary clinical trials results f=
or its PRIMA retinal implant. The patients in the trials had lost their cen=
tral visual field, which makes them unable to read and struggle to recogniz=
e faces. The results showed that the PRIMA implant restored real form visio=
n in these patients such that sequences of letters can be read with a clini=
cally meaningful improvement of letter acuity.
John 9:25 - Whether he is a sinner or not, I don't know. One thing I do kno=
w: I was blind but now I see.
Science (the Corporation, not the field of study) released very promising p=
reliminary results from clinical trials of its PRIMA retinal implant. The P=
RIMA system is a wireless, autonomous implant that works with special glass=
es and a pocket processor to enhance visual clarity. Essentially the glasse=
s capture an image and that image is transported to an implant in the patie=
nts eye that allows them a to =E2=80=9Csee=E2=80=9D a version of that image=
=2E
The implant restored meaningful vision to individuals who had lost their ce=
ntral visual field, enabling them to read sequences of letters and even lon=
ger texts. After 12 months, patients showed an average improvement of 23 le=
tters (4.6 lines) in visual acuity, with the best patient improving by 59 l=
etters (11.8 lines). Meaning, the trial participants went from being blind =
to being able to read short passages.
Brain-computer interfaces (BCI) are going to get a lot better in the coming=
 years. One day, I=E2=80=99m sure we=E2=80=99ll all have some chip planted =
in our brains that makes us superhuman. But it=E2=80=99s awesome to see tha=
t initial beneficiaries of these BCI advancements are the people who need i=
t most, be it quadriplegics or the visually impaired.=20
TL;DR Science and technology are giving sight back to the blind.=20
(5) Two Big AI Launches
From Runway: Introducing Act-One [ https://substack.com/redirect/c2e88eb4-7=
a9b-49d7-a080-30d85a3bdfcc?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXep=
KbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
I=E2=80=99ve never really understood how animation works. In my head it alw=
ays goes back to flipbook animation. That=E2=80=99s the technique where seq=
uential drawings on pages are flipped rapidly to create the illusion of mot=
ion. You likely made a flipbook animation in first grade. It was exhausting=
 and shitty. So when I see animated films today, I always imagine a team of=
 artists flipbooking their way through an intricate 2 hour long movie. Read=
er, that=E2=80=99s now how animation works today and it hasn=E2=80=99t work=
ed this way in a long, long time. But if you=E2=80=99re like me and that=E2=
=80=99s your base-level understanding of animation than this new product fr=
om Runway is going to blow your mind.
Runway=E2=80=99s Act-One generates expressive character animations using on=
ly an actor's video and voice=E2=80=94no extra equipment required. By captu=
ring the nuances of facial expressions and performances, Act-One translates=
 real-life acting into digital characters, even when proportions differ fro=
m the source.
It=E2=80=99s always kinda funny in the animated movies when the character k=
ind of resembles the actor (although it=E2=80=99s even funnier when the cha=
racter is totally different than the actor.) Like Maui in Moana. The Rock w=
as born to play Maui and Maui was likely created to be perfect for The Rock=
=2E This tech takes that connection to=20=
a whole other level and does so in a l=
ow-cost, no equipment way.
From Anthropic:  Computer Use [ https://substack.com/redirect/b79c9c01-79fa=
-4bbe-840b-1cefe1d06518?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbq=
Osa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Anthropic introduced a new capability called "computer use" for its Claude =
3.5 Sonnet AI model. Computer Use allows Claude to interact with computers =
in ways similar to human user. It can perform tasks like moving the cursor,=
 clicking buttons, typing text, and switching between windows or applicatio=
ns. You know, things we mere mortals regularly do on computers. Claude is e=
ssentially interpreting screenshots to understand what's on the screen and =
to determine how to complete given tasks.
You don=E2=80=99t have to extrapolate the demo of computer use too many yea=
rs down the line to see how a technology like this could be disruptive. The=
 majority of knowledge work done today consists of interpreting information=
 on a screen and then moving our cursor or making a few keystrokes based on=
 that that information. AI models have been good at the interpretation part=
 for a couple of years now, but computer use bridges the gap between interp=
retation and action in a real-world helpful way like no model has before. I=
t=E2=80=99s a little clunky today and for most people the prompts needed to=
 complete a simple task would take longer than actually just doing the task=
, but you can pretty easily imagine the future when much of the prompting i=
s abstracted away and descendants of computer use are automating much of th=
e knowledge economy=E2=80=99s work.
Fine by me: =E2=80=9CHey computer use, please write and publish this week=
=E2=80=99s edition of the Weekly Dose of Optimism.=E2=80=9D
EDIT: After writing the above passage, Anthropic added another feature to C=
laude [ https://substack.com/redirect/124f673f-0a69-4c73-9e3d-366087ec7785?=
j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]: the a=
bility to write and run code. Claude taking down another important segment =
of the knowledge workforce. Told you it was hard to keep up with everything=
=2E=20
Bonus: Stripe Confirms Plans to Acquire Stablecoin Platform Bridge [ https:=
//substack.com/redirect/a07d98f1-7ed4-4b89-a56a-f136d7b74d52?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOX=
AwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Emily Mason for Bloomberg
Stripe Inc. [ https://substack.com/redirect/728b7e6b-9544-4399-9860-1a3bae5=
76f13?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] =
co-founder and Chief Executive Officer Patrick Collison confirmed in a X po=
st  [ https://substack.com/redirect/ea1358db-7932-44fa-b2f6-8e2df45cb60f?j=
=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]on Monda=
y that the payments company plans to buy stablecoin startup Bridge=E2=80=A6=
Stripe will pay $1.1 billion, according to a person familiar with the matte=
r who asked not to be identified discussing private information.
Packy here. On Monday, Bridge confirmed the rumors that Stripe would acquir=
e the company for $1.1 billion. This is both the largest acquisition in Str=
ipe=E2=80=99s history and the largest acquisition in crypto history.=20
Bridge is both a Not Boring Capital portfolio company and founded by Duke g=
rads, so personally, I=E2=80=99m psyched about the deal, but more important=
ly, this is a really big deal for the way that money moves around the world=
=2E Stablecoins are just better, faster=
, cheaper infrastructure for moving mo=
ney, and Stripe has both the scale and talent to make stablecoins the defau=
lt much more quickly.=20
As Stripe co-founder Patrick Collison tweeted, =E2=80=9CStablecoins are roo=
m-temperature superconductors for financial services. Thanks to stablecoins=
, businesses around the world will benefit from significant speed, coverage=
, and cost improvements in the coming years.=E2=80=9D
Something like this was inevitable. When I wrote about Stripe [ https://sub=
stack.com/redirect/985c4c41-d1d0-4127-ab2d-9955aa71d0b9?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3Q=
ifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] back in August 2020, I pr=
edicted that it would want to eventually rebuild economic infrastructure fr=
om the ground up, and acquiring Bridge is a big step in that direction.=20
Now, we=E2=80=99re going to get to see how much more creative leverage entr=
epreneurs can unlock if they get ~2% of their revenue back to spend on more=
 productive uses.
Have a great weekend y=E2=80=99all.
